\begin<<267>>tex2html_deferred<<267>>\par\end<<268>>tex2html_deferred<<268>>\question A signal given by \begin<<123>>tex2html_wrap_inline<<123>>$x(t) = a_1\sin(\omega t+\phi_1)$\end<<124>>tex2html_wrap_inline<<124>>\space is applied to a stable linear time-invariant system. Suppose the steady state output response of the system is given by \begin<<125>>tex2html_wrap_inline<<125>>$a_2F(\omega_2 t +\phi_2)$\end<<126>>tex2html_wrap_inline<<126>>. Then which of the following is true about the function \begin<<127>>tex2html_wrap_inline<<127>>$F$\end<<128>>tex2html_wrap_inline<<128>>? (\textbf<<9>>2 marks<<9>>)
\begin<<10>>itemize<<10>>
    \item F is not necessarily `sine' or `cosine', but must be periodic with \begin<<129>>tex2html_wrap_inline<<129>>$\omega_1=\omega_2$\end<<130>>tex2html_wrap_inline<<130>>.
    \item F must be a `sine' or a `cosine' function with \begin<<131>>tex2html_wrap_inline<<131>>$a_1=a_2$\end<<132>>tex2html_wrap_inline<<132>>
    \item F must be a `sine' function with \begin<<133>>tex2html_wrap_inline<<133>>$\omega_1=\omega_2$\end<<134>>tex2html_wrap_inline<<134>>\space and \begin<<135>>tex2html_wrap_inline<<135>>$\phi_1=\phi_2$\end<<136>>tex2html_wrap_inline<<136>>
    \item F must be a `sine' or `cosine' function with \begin<<137>>tex2html_wrap_inline<<137>>$\omega_1=\omega_2$\end<<138>>tex2html_wrap_inline<<138>>.
\end<<11>>itemize<<11>>
\begin<<269>>tex2html_deferred<<269>>\par\end<<270>>tex2html_deferred<<270>>\question A continuous-time system is described by \begin<<139>>tex2html_wrap_inline<<139>>$y(t)=e^<<12>>-|x(t)|<<12>>$\end<<140>>tex2html_wrap_inline<<140>>, where \begin<<141>>tex2html_wrap_inline<<141>>$y(t)$\end<<142>>tex2html_wrap_inline<<142>>\space is the output and \begin<<143>>tex2html_wrap_inline<<143>>$x(t)$\end<<144>>tex2html_wrap_inline<<144>>\space is the input. The output signal \begin<<145>>tex2html_wrap_inline<<145>>$y(t)$\end<<146>>tex2html_wrap_inline<<146>>\space is bounded (\textbf<<13>>2 marks<<13>>)
\begin<<14>>itemize<<14>>
    \item only when \begin<<147>>tex2html_wrap_inline<<147>>$x(t)$\end<<148>>tex2html_wrap_inline<<148>>\space is bounded.
    \item only when \begin<<149>>tex2html_wrap_inline<<149>>$x(t)$\end<<150>>tex2html_wrap_inline<<150>>\space is non-negative
    \item only for \begin<<151>>tex2html_wrap_inline<<151>>$t \leq 0$\end<<152>>tex2html_wrap_inline<<152>>\space if \begin<<153>>tex2html_wrap_inline<<153>>$x(t)$\end<<154>>tex2html_wrap_inline<<154>>\space is bounded for \begin<<155>>tex2html_wrap_inline<<155>>$t \geq 0$\end<<156>>tex2html_wrap_inline<<156>>
    \item even when \begin<<157>>tex2html_wrap_inline<<157>>$x(t)$\end<<158>>tex2html_wrap_inline<<158>>\space is non-negative.
\end<<15>>itemize<<15>>
\begin<<271>>tex2html_deferred<<271>>\par\end<<272>>tex2html_deferred<<272>>\question A system is represented by the following input-output relationship, (\textbf<<16>>2 marks<<16>>)
\begin<<17>>align*<<17>>
    y(t) = \int_<<18>>-\infty<<18>>^<<19>>8t<<19>>x(\tau) d \tau \quad;\quad t;SPMgt;0
\end<<20>>align*<<20>>
Which is true about this system?
\begin<<21>>itemize<<21>>
    \item Linear and Causal
    \item Linear but not Causal
    \item Causal but not linear
    \item Neither causal nor linear
\end<<22>>itemize<<22>>
